<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n08104a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08104a">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08104a"> 104(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> inshore breeze / dismasted / deck awash / lose sight of each other</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><b>Twelve Days in an Open Boat / Adrift in the Indian Ocean</b> <br> Further news of the Indian Ocean venture of the men of the lost sailing vessel, Kassa, adds fresh lustre to the annals of the Mercantile Marine.<font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> The five survivors <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> state that their vessel <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> was caught in a hurricane about 800 miles east of Madagascar, was <mark>dismasted</mark>, became waterlogged, and ultimately had to be abandoned on January 4, the <mark>decks being then awash</mark>.<font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> <b>A Welcoming Sight</b> On Jan. 15 the mate&apos;s boat, shortly after sunrise, saw a faint blue outline as of land in the south-west <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> The stormy weather abated, and, with an <mark>inshore breeze</mark> the boat headed for the welcoming land. <small> <a name="II23jan24" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#II23jan24"><cite title="source">Irish Independent</cite></a> (23 January 1924) 9/6</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c02254a" href="c02all.htm#c02254a">VI.C.02:254(a)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
